    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-01-10T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-01-10T15:00:00-05:00" n="881"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d881">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">890D.927/90: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-01-10T20:00:00+00:00"
                            >January 10, 1939—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received January 10—5:35 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>55. Department’s 22, January 9, 8 p.m. Lagarde<note n="5" xml:id="d881fn5">Ernest
                        Lagarde, Chief of the Africa-Levant Section of the French Foreign
                        Office.</note> has promised to send appropriate telegraphic instructions at
                    once to both Ankara and Beirut. He acknowledged full French responsibility for
                    seeing that the contract is fulfilled and said that everything possible “within
                    the limits of amicable negotiation” would be done. He expressed the opinion that
                    juridically the Turks could possibly make a case on the grounds that the
                    Franco-Turkish agreement of 1937<note n="5a" xml:id="d881fn5a">Signed at Geneva,
                        May 29, 1937, League of Nations, <hi rend="italic">Official Journal</hi>,
                        November 1937, p. 838.</note> does not make “internal agreements” binding
                    for the new order in the Hatay but added that he did not believe that they would
                    make an issue of the point in this particular instance. He was definitely of the
                    opinion that the matter should be left entirely in the hands of the French
                    authorities, except as circumstances may require some direct contract between
                    the Committee’s representative and the Hatay authorities.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
